<subSubSection lastPageId="67" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1770,2011]" lastBlockId="67.[151,1436,151,752]" lastPageId="67" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1950,1975]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Description.</emphasis>
Massive digitate sponge, tubular structures irregular and low, 160 × 140 × 
<quantity box="[1226,1322,1951,1975]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="100.0">100 mm</quantity>
diameter, body attached to common base (
<figureCitation box="[523,629,1986,2011]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="67.[151,250,1781,1803]" captionTargetBox="[150,1403,793,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@67.[150,1403,793,1761]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURE 30. Psammocinia alba sp. nov. A. In situ; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x10)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651510/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 30A</figureCitation>
). Surface conulose, with oscules on low tubular structures, 
<quantity box="[1311,1406,1986,2011]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Ostia visible, small, ± 
<quantity box="[523,611,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter, randomly scattered over the surface of the sponge. Texture soft and spongy, very compressible, difficult to tear. Colour in life, white with a pale lilac-tinge, interior pale-beige; in preservative white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="67.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,260,285]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[318,454,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="67.[151,250,1781,1803]" captionTargetBox="[150,1403,793,1761]" captionTargetId="figure@67.[150,1403,793,1761]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURE 30. Psammocinia alba sp. nov. A. In situ; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x10)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651510/files/figure.png" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Fig. 30B, C</figureCitation>
). Choanosomal skeleton consists of irregular primary fibres cored with sand granules, 190 (150–210) µm in diameter. Secondary fibres are 85 (51–98) µm in diameter, also cored with sand granules.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="67.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,1371,332,357]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,652,332,357]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Substratum, depth range and ecology.</emphasis>
This sponge was found on a rocky overhang at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[1307,1371,332,356]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" type="generic">
<quantity box="[1307,1367,332,356]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="67" pageNumber="68" unit="m" value="23.0">23 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="67.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,965,367,392]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,495,367,392]" pageId="67" pageNumber="68">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
